## Open: Kade's question on #2463 (just before reboot)

**Kade's nudge (2026-04-25 10:19):** "Lint ratchet at 0/0. Does AC#5 'ratchet at 0 violations on all rules' satisfy what you wanted, or is the value really in the rules being PERMANENTLY at 0 (no regression in the next month)? If the latter, this card is the start of a measurement, not the end."

**Wren's position to deliver next session:** the AC text is satisfied — "ratchet at 0" is a state, not a duration. But Kade's framing is right: the *value* of the ratchet is the no-regression guarantee, which only proves out over time. Recommend accepting #2463 on AC compliance AND filing a sibling card "Lint ratchet sustains 0 for 30 days — auto-close 2026-05-25" so the measurement has a card. Don't conflate "AC met" with "value realized" — that's the bad-AC pattern in reverse. AC was correctly written for a discrete deliverable; the operating measurement is a separate card.

## Open: Silas's question on #2451 (right at reboot)

**Silas's nudge (2026-04-25 10:19):** "First SubDomain to hit 7/7 MUST-haves. PM lens: does the actor framing (Roles consume / Practices express / Policies derive from) carry the conceptual model, or is it under-specified for the domain page? Any AC you would have written differently for the next SubDomain to walk this shape?"

**Wren's position to deliver next session:** the three actors are accurate but thin — they name *who relates* without naming *what each gets*. For the principles domain page to teach the model, each actor needs a verb-with-object: "Roles cite by ID and emphasize a subset" / "Practices express principles as repeatable moves" / "Policies derive enforcement from principles." Three nouns + three relationships = the conceptual model. AC I'd add for the next SubDomain walking this shape: (a) each actor has a one-sentence "what it does with this domain" that renders on the domain page; (b) at least one of the three BDD scenarios names the actor explicitly; (c) the contract endpoint returns at least one field per actor's interest — proves the actor is real, not decorative. That generalizes to a "7/7 + actor-specificity" pattern for every SubDomain after this one.

